[There are a number of anomalies in these reports. It usually takes some 3-4 days minimum before any skin lesions develop, and as this animal was probably butchered just before the weekend there would not have been much of a carcass left if identification of the problem followed the clinical onset of the human case. The nature of veterinary involvement before, during, or after slaughter is unclear, but probably minimal from the official comments. They were fortunate to have some bits available to be sent for confirmation in Sofia. I suspect that the human case was diagnosed clinically and not as a result of any laboratory action as the Food Agency officer is still awaiting veterinary laboratory confirmation. Thus why this has been posted as a "suspect" case for the moment.

Anthrax is sporadic in Bulgarian livestock, affecting both cattle, sheep and goats, largely in Ruse and Yambol in north east Bulgaria. To see a map of Bulgaria, go to http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/europe/bulgaria.jpg
Shumen: http://www.fallingrain.com/world/BU/54/Shumen.html
Takach/Takatsch/Tukach: http://www.fallingrain.com/world/BU/54/Tukach.html - Mod.MHJ]
